<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>AC has NOTHING to do with mitigation. NOTHING. Mitigation works in a simple way, look at disc defensive or combat stability. Every hit gets a certain % knocked off. So, at 10% mitigation, 1000 becomes 900.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Sigh. Baby jeebus is crying. <br>
<br>
\Mit&quot;i*gate\, v. t. [imp. &amp; p. p. Mitigated; p. pr. &amp; vb. n. Mitigating.] [L. mitigatus, p. p. of mitigare to soften, mitigate; mitis mild, soft + the root of agere to do, drive.] 1. To make less severe, intense, harsh, rigorous, painful, etc.; to soften; to meliorate; to alleviate; to diminish; to lessen; as, to mitigate heat or cold; to mitigate grief.<br>
<br>
mitigate<br>
<br>
v : lessen or to try to lessen the seriousness or extent of<br>
<br>
<br>
You are saying that AC plays no part in mitigation and that only a discipline that lowers damage reduction by lowering the effective DI of the mob counts? I'm assuming adding raw equipment AC that lowers the average hit doesn't qualify, since of course that doesn't &quot;lessen the severity of&quot; of the mobs attacks...right? Semantics. Fine...replace the word mitigate with &quot;reduce damage per hit&quot; in Ninaor's post. Happy? You completely missed his point, which was that WAR class specific gear typically has higher hp/AC than the knight class specific gear. Whether you agree that it is a valid argument or not is another story, but you didn't even address his argument, you went off on a wild tangent.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Just like ATK bonuses can't change how hard your maximum non-crit hit is.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Wrong. Increasing attack increases your max hit up to a threshold that is dependent on class and level. Find a level 60 warrior with 1000 atk and parse long enough to find his max hit. Now give him enough STR buffs/gear and +atk buffs/gear to raise his atk considerably and then find his max hit. At level 60 it will top out at 5.7 times weapon damage plus damage bonus...but not until he has reached a certain atk threshold. 1000 atk is well below that threshold.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>If you want an illustration of how AC works, fight AoW. AoW has a very high ATK rating. I don't think anyone can attain high enough AC to match his ATK. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
You sure about this? I'd love to see the data from you tanking AoW with 1800 AC. I'm sure there is a level 65 warrior with high AC that can tank AoW and post a histogram. Might be enlightening.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>As for not talking about tables. Tables determine your tanking ability. The fact that you relate tables exclusively to tanking naked shows exactly how little you know. So get a clue before your spew junior.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
The fact that you didn't seem to comprehend what he was saying probably explains this passage. Where did he relate tanking naked with defensive tables? He simply made the point that you generally DON'T tank naked, and that gear plays a part in your tanking ability. Would you argue otherwise?<br>
<br>
&quot;shows exactly how little you know&quot; <br>
<br>
I would say that quote shows 1.) how poorly you understood what he was actually saying, and 2.) how quickly you resorted to ad hominem attacks.  <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=14686">Graal MacBladefury</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
